          "title": "The desolate city — worship silenced, honor inverted (1:4-7)",
          "body": "Verses 4-7 describe the ruin in its civic and liturgical dimensions. The roads of Zion mourn — not merely the people on them but the roads themselves, personified as mourners. The appointed feasts (moed) that organized Israel's year — Passover, Weeks, Tabernacles — are silent. The gates, once the city's commercial and judicial center, are desolate. Priests groan; virgins are afflicted; Jerusalem herself is bitter. Every social class is named in its suffering: priests (worship), virgins (the city's future), the people (1:11), the princes (1:6, now like deer finding no pasture). The theological sharpness of verse 5 interrupts the catalog of loss: 'the LORD has caused her grief because of the multitude of her transgressions.' The poet refuses to let the suffering remain purely descriptive. There is a cause. Verse 7's memory of 'the precious things that were from the days of old' deepens the sorrow — Jerusalem's suffering includes the torment of remembering what she once was. The adversaries see her and mock."
